{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636682"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:32:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:32:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17599"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17599"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75475"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10313"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17599"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60985"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7754"},{"type":"tags","id":"7824"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24175"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75475"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is designing a study to investigate whether a new medication reduces blood pressure compared to placebo. They want to ensure their statistical analysis is robust.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a Type I error in this context?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Incorrectly concluding the medication reduces blood pressure when it does not","Correctly identifying that the medication does not reduce blood pressure","Correctly identifying that the medication reduces blood pressure","Incorrectly concluding the medication does not reduce blood pressure when it does","Increasing the sample size to improve statistical power"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EType I error (false positive)\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when the null hypothesis is incorrectly rejected. In this case, it means concluding the medication is effective when it actually isn\u0027t. This is controlled by setting the significance level (\u03b1), typically at 0.05.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncorrectly concluding the medication does not reduce blood pressure when it does\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a Type II error (false negative)\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorrectly identifying that the medication reduces blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a true positive, not an error\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorrectly identifying that the medication does not reduce blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a true negative, not an error\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the sample size to improve statistical power\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a study design consideration that reduces the risk of Type II error\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding Type I and Type II errors is crucial for interpreting research results. Type I error rate (\u03b1) is set by the researcher, while Type II error rate (\u03b2) depends on sample size, effect size, and variability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type I error (false positive) occurs when rejecting a true null hypothesis","Type II error (false negative) occurs when failing to reject a false null hypothesis","Statistical power is the probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis (1 - probability of Type II error)"],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60985"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17599"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60985"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T21:03:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T00:54:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10313"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75475"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d